## SpaceWire Channel Management (`spw_channel.c`)

### Core Structures

Channels are **statically allocated** — no dynamic memory:

```c
/* Statically allocated channel arrays */
static spw_channel_element_t spw_channel_elements[SPW_MAX_CHANNEL_ELEMENTS];
static spw_channel_t         spw_channels[SPW_MAX_CHANNELS];
```

The `spw_channel_t` struct carries the UIO mapping alongside SpaceWire identifiers:

```c
typedef struct {
    uint8_t   uio_id;       // Maps this SPW channel to a UIO channel slot
    uint8_t   dir;          // Direction: in, out, inout
    uint8_t   device_id;    // STAR-Dundee device index (ground) or FPGA IF id (flight)
    uint8_t   channel_id;   // SDK channel index within device
    bool      is_open;      // Safety gate — prevents double-open
} spw_channel_t;
```

### Safe Initialization Pattern

All channels are zeroed and set to invalid before use:

```c
static void channel_clear(spw_channel_t *channel_ptr)
{
    channel_ptr->uio_id    = SPW_CHANNEL_ID_INVALID;
    channel_ptr->is_open   = false;
    // ... zero all other fields
}
```

`spw_channel_open()` defensively returns `true` immediately if `is_open` is already set —
preventing redundant state mutation. All pointer arguments are checked against `NULL` before
dereferencing.

### load_defs()

Channel definitions are populated at startup by `load_defs()`, which reads properties
(`uio_id`, `dir`, `device_id`, `channel_id`) from configuration and maps them into the
static `spw_channels` array. This is the only place channel-to-UIO bindings are established.

### Queued (Buffered) Mode

Channels can be opened in queued mode to buffer incoming traffic when no receive operation
is pending — equivalent to `buffered = 1` in `STAR_openChannelToLocalDevice()`. Always use
queued mode for RX-capable channels to prevent packet loss.

