## Camera → SpaceWire Dispatch Pattern

Camera hardware commands are dispatched over SpaceWire via `spw_write()`. The typical
pattern in `cam_model_caspex_cmv4k.c`:

```c
// Build a hex command buffer specific to the CMV4K register protocol
static void build_reg_write_cmd(uint8_t *buf, uint16_t reg_addr, uint16_t value)
{
    buf[0] = CAM_CMD_WRITE_REG;
    buf[1] = (uint8_t)(reg_addr >> 8);
    buf[2] = (uint8_t)(reg_addr & 0xFF);
    buf[3] = (uint8_t)(value >> 8);
    buf[4] = (uint8_t)(value & 0xFF);
}

// Dispatch via spw_write():
uint8_t cmd_buf[CAM_CMD_BUF_SIZE];
build_reg_write_cmd(cmd_buf, reg_addr, value);
bool ok = spw_write(spw_channel_ptr, cmd_buf, sizeof(cmd_buf));
if (!ok) {
    evr_report_error_2(CAM_EVR_SPW_WRITE_FAIL, reg_addr);
}
```

> **Note**: Many advanced configuration commands (gain, exposure) are currently stubbed
> with `log_store()` placeholders. These must be replaced with actual `spw_write()` calls
> before delivery.

The camera execution model is **asynchronous**:
- A tick-based RTOS semaphore drives `cam_main()` each cycle
- `cam_main()` evaluates pending flags set by the command router and dispatches actions
- State mutations are protected by `lock()`/`unlock()` on the device mutex
- Long-running hardware operations do not block the command ingester

